<font color="#FF0000">NKP 68-69</font><br>
<tt>Tue Sep  9 14:18:18 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I was a Combat Photog with Det 12 601st Photo Sq.for two tours in 68 &amp; 69.<br>
Flew with 23TASS - O2a,602nd SOS - A1-E, Nimrods - A-26, &amp; Jolly Greens.<br><br>
Remember one day we had returned from a morning mission over the &quot;Trail&quot;. We landed and were sitting on the taxiway waiting for Sandys to take off. First plane got off okay. #2 started his roll. Halfway down the runway he lost power. The tail settled down as he passed us. Seconds later he pancaked into the ditch at the end of the runway. He was fully loaded for a rescue. The centerline ruptured and exploded. We had just left dearm area so were about 30 yards from the crash. We shutdown, exited the aircraft PDQ and headed for cover. God was watching over that pilot, though. The Jollys were hovering in their area for departure to the rescue. The lead Jolly quickly flew over the downed plane, hovered, suppressing the flames, and lowered a parmedic. The pilot had tried to crawl out but his harness was hung up. He was burned on his arms and legs. Because of God and that Jolly Green crew, he survived sure death.<br>
BTW, the object of the rescue, an F4 crew, was rescued later that day.<br><br>
I was so fired up I went back to the area in an A-1E. We got to the area just as the backseat was rescued and had the pleasure of cleaning up the area.<br><br>

